### run terminal window
[Ctrl+Alt+T]
## terminator
	# split verticaly
	[Ctrl+Shift+E]
	# split horizontaly
	[Ctrl+Shift+O]

### application finder
[Alt+F2]

# https://help.ubuntu.com/community/find
o@o-ecb:/$ find / -iname '*filename*' > ~/found

# To show history from all terminals:
# Add export PROMPT_COMMAND='history -a; history -r' to your .bashrc file.
# https://askubuntu.com/questions/80371/bash-history-handling-with-multiple-terminals#80380
	# https://askubuntu.com/questions/80371/bash-history-handling-with-multiple-terminals#comment-90735
# https://askubuntu.com/questions/80371/bash-history-handling-with-multiple-terminals#369184

# run a jar
# example -> java -jar runmy.jar
$ java -jar yed.jar

## PPA - Personal Package Archive
# https://launchpad.net/+help-soyuz/ppa-sources-list.html
	#check also https://help.ubuntu.com/community/Repositories/CommandLine
# PPA's location-> ppa:user/ppa-name //example-> ppa:pasgui/ppa
# add a repository to the system
#sudo add-apt-repository ppa:user/ppa-name
o@o-ecb:~$ sudo add-apt-repository ppa:pasgui/ppa
# update list of latest available software from the repositories in /etc/apt/sources.list
o@o-ecb:~$ sudo apt-get update
# install software
o@o-ecb:~$ sudo apt-get install douml

## Check Ubuntu release
# LSB = Linux Standard Base
# https://askubuntu.com/questions/150917/what-terminal-command-checks-the-ubuntu-version#150947
#$ lsb_release [-d|-c|-r|-a]
$ lsb_release -d
$ cat /etc/lsb-release
# more
$ cat /etc/*release
$ cat /etc/issue
$ uname -a
# [Alt+F2] "gnome-system-monitor"
## nice approach (didn't work on ubuntu 14.04)
	#https://askubuntu.com/questions/12493/how-can-i-find-the-version-of-ubuntu-that-is-installed#21998
# enter in navigator bar : "ghelp:about-ubuntu"
# [Alt+F2] "gnome-help ghelp:about-ubuntu"



